    54	  A day or two later I decided to give a few of the local boards a call, only to
    55	find that the most active sub-boards around were abuse!  After reading a dozen
    56	or so messages I came across a message that was insulting my personal favorite
    57	BBS, The Digital Dimension, on-line since Aug.	1983, a VERY nice system.  The
    58	post was saying how bad the board was because the SysOp wouldn't give him high
    59	access, and never answer- ed [F]eedback, or [C]hats.  I was pretty upset, the
    60	SysOp is a personal friend so I naturally [P]osted about the matter and
    61	explained how he is a very busy person and tries to do as much as he can, after
    62	all there are over 750 users!  Feeling satisfied I logged off and observed a few
    63	other local boards only to find more abuse, hatred, and destruction.  I then
    64	decided I would go outside and get some fresh air and live a nornal life, after
    65	all I don't want to take the image of a 'computer freak'.  A day later, very
    66	concerned, I again auto-dialed to same board with Matthew Dornquast's beloved
    67	Megaterm.  After about a half an hour of dialing I heard the computer in the
    68	other room signal that a ring was detected.  I came in the room and went through
    69	the logon procedures and went staight to the abuse board to find about 10 new
    70	mess- gaes after mine!	I began to read them; more of the same hatred.	I then
    71	came to a post about 4 after mine by the person that I posted about.  He told me
    72	off and posted my number.  I was very uneasy, I have never heard of the guy
    73	before and he posted my number!  Not sure to post or not I sat there for a
    74	minute and said why not.  Not bothering to read the other new messages I
    75	[P]osted.  I then told him how everyone had their own right to say what they
    76	want and that posting number solved nothing.  Of course later that week, for
    77	about three days I received prank calls, I would pick up the phone with an
    78	"Hello?" Nothing.  He would just sit there, hoping that I would get upset with
    79	his deed.  This will make him happy.  I then started to tell him how much of a
    80	man he was by prank calling, he was proba- bly expecting to here "We have a
    81	trace on our line blah blah blah!" I then hung up.  He never called back.  Later
    82	on that day my very good SysOp friend of The Digital Dimension called me.  He
    83	started to explain how he was told earier today that he was going to be moving
    84	at the end of this school year.  He then asked me very seriously 'Bryan, will
    85	you please run a copy of the board in Houston while I take a copy to Iowa.' I
    86	thought long and hard, being a SysOp required alot of work, time, and devotion.
    87	A whole lot.  I agreed.  Many things were now needed to be done.  Now relizing
    88	that I didn't have the hard- ware to support the system, that week- ened I
    89	started a buying spree.  I first bought my Sider 10 Megabyte hard drive, $695.
    90	Then bought a Thunderclock, another $110.  I of course needed a firmware chip
    91	for my cat, $30.  And so my computer won't overheat, a System Saver, $70.  I
    92	then relized that I would need my own phone line so I called the phone company
    93	and got it installed, $120.  Relizing how many callers I would loose if the
    94	number changed, I would have to pay an additional $60 to get the same number,
    95	713/497-4633 but that will have to wait 'till he moves.  After realizing I just
    96	spent over a thousand dollars just to get the board started I began to get use
    97	to the software.  It was a home brew.  Nevertheless, a very nice one.  I started
    98	to write new "mods" and features for the board.  I only had a print out of the
    99	board then so the SysOp could get his software copyright- ed.  Knowing that in
   100	order to keep the high quality of the system it would require many long nights
   101	over the key- board, more night then ever before.  Typing...  thinking...
   102	working...  programming.  After showing the SysOp my progress, he was quite
   103	pleased.  I rewrote many functions.  Many features were now more efficient and
   104	faster then before.  I also started the begining of our soon to be enormous
   105	[L]ibrary on our new 'baby' the 10 Meg Sider.
